04348nam a22006975i 9781442688148DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426881487 a10.3138/97814426881482doi  a(DE-B1597)497051  a(OCoLC)1078918450  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPN1995b.G3813 2009eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4301/51 aGaudreault, Andre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Plato to Lumière :bNarration and Monstration in Literature and Cinema /cAndre Gaudreault. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tPreface to the English-language edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Early Cinema and Narrativity -- t2. Narrative Problems -- t3. In Search of the First Film Narrative -- t4. Early Narratology: Mimesis and Diegesis -- t5. Textual Narrative and Staged Narrative -- t6. Narration and Monstration -- t7. The Narrator and the Monstrator -- t8. Narration and Monstration in the Cinema -- t9. The Film Narrative System -- t10. The Origins of the Film Narrator -- t11. Narrator(s) -- t12. A Monstrative Entertainment, Assisted by Narration -- t13. Delegated Film Narrators -- tConclusion -- tAfterword (1998): Cinema, Between Literariness and Intermediality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith this lucid translation of Du litteraire au filmique, André Gaudreault's highly influential and original study of film narratology is now accessible to English-language audiences for the first time. Building a theory of narrative on sources as diverse as Plato, The Arabian Nights,and Proust, From Plato to Lumière challenges narratological orthodoxy by positing that all forms of narrative are mediated by an "underlying narrator" who exists between the author and narrative text. Offering illuminating insights, definitions, and formal distinctions, Gaudreault examines the practices of novelists, playwrights, and filmmakers and applies his theory to the early cinema of the Lumière brothers and more recent films. He also enhances our understanding of how narrative develops visually without language - monstration - by detailing how the evolution of the medium influenced narratives in cinema. From Plato to Lumière includes a translation of Paul Ricoeur's preface to the French-language edition as well as a new preface by Tom Gunning. It is a must-read for cinema and media students and scholars and an essential text on the study of narrative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picture playsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBarnard, Timothy.1 aGunning, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268814840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442688148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442688148.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK